               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18311201-283-person2124">
                  JOSEPH 
                  ALLEN
               <interp inst="t18311201-283-person2124" type="surname" value="ALLEN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-283-person2124" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-283-person2124" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a <rs id="t18311201-283-viclabel1505" type="occupation">gardener</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18311201-283-victim2123 t18311201-283-viclabel1505"></join>, and live in Lissongrove. On the afternoon of the 2nd of December, I was in <placeName id="t18311201-283-crimeloc1506">the Champion public-house, in Earl-street, Lisson-grove</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18311201-283-crimeloc1506" type="placeName" value="the Champion public-house, in Earl-street, Lisson-grove"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18311201-283-crimeloc1506" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18311201-283-off1503 t18311201-283-crimeloc1506"></join>; I had some bread and meat, which I laid down - I counted my money before I went in, as I had been taking up some trees, and did not know exactly what I had; I found I had 13s. in silver in my right-hand coat pocket, and 11 1/2d. in my left-hand coat pocket - I put three half-crowns in my breast-pocket, leaving the other, which was in sixpences and shillings, in my coat pocket; I went into the tap-room, had a pint of beer, and saw the prisoner sitting in another box by the fire - I was rather fresh with liquor; I fell into a dose - I was not exactly fast asleep; I felt the prisoner's hand in my pocket - I took hold of it; he ran across into the box where he came from; I charged him with picking my pocket, as I found I had not one farthing left, and told him I would serve him out for it - I went to the door, sent a man for a Policeman, and staid outside the door a quarter of an hour or twenty minutes, while he went for him.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. J. ALLEY. Q.When are you paid your wages? A. At uncertain times; I had then been at work for Mrs. Lewis, North-bank - I had taken 24s.; I was not very drunk: when I get a little liquor it takes my head, and I have been desired by publicans to stay away from their houses; I had another pint of porter at Maida-hill, and one at the Portman Arms, in the afternoon - I had had no ale nor spirits that day, and I had one pint at the Champion; I carried my silver in my coat pocket, because both my trousers pockets were torn - I went in behind the door of the Champion; I did not see any one but the prisoner - he sat between two women in a box in a corner; there might be other persons in the room; I sat by myself - there was no one in the next box- I did not want any man in the room to fight, that I will swear; I was not exactly asleep - I should have been asleep if I had not been disturbed; the prisoner's hand was in my pocket, and I caught hold of it - he twisted it from me, and went back to his seat; I told him I would serve him out - I went out in a moment for the Policeman; I do not know how many persons were there - there were several persons in the room when the Policeman came; I was very much agitated - I sent an Irish labourer for a Policeman; he was a stranger to me - I gave him a shilling yesterday morning - the prisoner did not attempt to run away, but staid in the room between the two women - I have charged several persons with robbing me; I never took any body up - I have been robbed there before.</p>
               <p>COURT. Q. How many persons were in the room when you went out for an officer? A. I did not take any notice - the prisoner and the women were there; there might be other men.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18311201-283-person2125">
                  STEPHEN 
                  HAYWARD
               <interp inst="t18311201-283-person2125" type="surname" value="HAYWARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-283-person2125" type="given" value="STEPHEN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-283-person2125" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Police-officer. I went<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183112010120"></xptr>to the Champion public-house, in Earl-street; the prosecutor stood at the door - he said there was a man inside who had picked his pocket; he appeared very fresh - he did not appear as if he could know if a person's hand was in his pocket - he did not appear able to take care of himself; I took the prisoner to the watch-house, and there searched him - there might be seven or eight persons in the tap-room; I did not search the prisoner till I got to Harcourt-street, which is half a mile from the house; I found on him a knife, a key, and 2 1/2d. - I do not think the prosecutor could tell whether he had hold of a man's arm or not.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18311201-283-verdict1507" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18311201-283-verdict1507" type="verdictCategory" value="notGuilty"></interp>
               NOT GUILTY
            </rs>.</p>
